    cellular: { title: "Mechanisms of Polypharmacy-Related Harm", content: "Polypharmacy-related harm arises through several interconnected mechanisms that compound with each additional medication. Drug-drug interactions (DDIs) occur at pharmacokinetic (absorption, distribution, metabolism, excretion) and pharmacodynamic (additive, synergistic, or antagonistic effects at receptors) levels. The probability of a clinically significant DDI increases exponentially: 5 medications = 50% chance; 7 medications = 82%; ≥10 medications approaches 100%.\n\nAge-related pharmacokinetic changes in older adults amplify polypharmacy risks: decreased hepatic blood flow and CYP450 activity reduce drug metabolism; declining GFR reduces renal clearance; decreased lean body mass and increased adiposity alter volume of distribution; reduced serum albumin increases free drug fraction of highly protein-bound drugs. Pharmacodynamic changes include increased receptor sensitivity (benzodiazepines, opioids, anticholinergics) and impaired homeostatic mechanisms (baroreceptor reflexes, thermoregulation).\n\nThe anticholinergic burden is a critical concept: many commonly prescribed medications have anticholinergic properties (diphenhydramine, oxybutynin, TCAs, first-generation antipsychotics, muscle relaxants). Cumulative anticholinergic exposure causes cognitive impairment, delirium, falls, constipation, urinary retention, dry mouth, and blurred vision. The anticholinergic cognitive burden (ACB) scale quantifies this cumulative risk." },
