    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of POTS", content: "Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS) is a form of dysautonomia characterized by an excessive heart rate increase upon standing (≥30 bpm in adults, ≥40 bpm in adolescents, or sustained HR >120 bpm within 10 minutes of standing) without orthostatic hypotension (blood pressure does not drop significantly). Symptoms include lightheadedness, palpitations, presyncope, exercise intolerance, brain fog, and fatigue.\n\nSeveral subtypes exist with different pathophysiology: (1) Neuropathic POTS: partial autonomic neuropathy affecting lower extremity sympathetic nerves, causing blood pooling in the legs upon standing (most common subtype); (2) Hyperadrenergic POTS: excessive norepinephrine release upon standing (plasma NE >600 pg/mL), causing tachycardia, tremor, and hypertension; (3) Hypovolemic POTS: reduced blood volume (often with low renin-aldosterone) causing inadequate cardiac filling when upright.\n\nPOTS predominantly affects women (5:1 ratio) aged 15-50. Common triggers include viral infection (especially COVID-19 — POTS is a recognized manifestation of Long COVID), surgery, pregnancy, and deconditioning. There is significant overlap with joint hypermobility syndrome/Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (hypermobile type), mast cell activation syndrome, and ME/CFS." },
